<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="sec-argument-and-validity">
    <title>Argument and Validity</title>

    <assemblage xml:id="assemblage-obj-intro">
        <title>Section Objectives</title>

        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    Define argument (or logical deduction)
                </li>

                <li>
                    Identify hypothesis and conclusion of a given argument
                </li>

                <li>
                    Determine the validity of an argument using a truth table
                </li>

                <li>
                    Determine the validity of an argument using rules of inferences
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </assemblage>


    <paragraphs>
        <title>Basic Concepts of Arguments</title>

        <definition >
            <statement>
                <p>
                    An argument (logical deduction) is an assertion that a given set of statements <m>p_{1},\,p_{2},\dots,p_{n}</m>, called <m>\textbf{hypotheses}</m> or <em><m>\textbf{premises}</m></em>, yield another statement <m>\textbf{Q}</m>, called the <m>\textbf{conclusion}</m>.
                    Such a logical deduction is denoted by:
                </p>

                <tabular>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>p_{1},</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>p_{2},</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\ldots,</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>p_{n}</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\vdash\;Q \,\, \text{ or}</m></cell>
                    </row>

                    <row>
                        <cell><m>p_{1}</m></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                    </row>

                    <row>
                        <cell><m>p_{2}</m></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                    </row>

                    <row>
                        <cell><m>\\ \vdots\\</m></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                    </row>

                    <row>
                        <cell><m>\frac{p_{n}}{Q}</m></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </statement>
        </definition>

        <example>
            <p>
                Consider the following argument:
            </p>

            <p>
                If you study hard, then you will pass the exam.
            </p>

            <p>
                You did not pass the exam.
            </p>

            <p>
                Therefore, you did not study hard.
            </p>

            <p>
                Let <m>p</m>: You study hard.
            </p>

            <p>
                <m >\qquad q</m>: You will pass the exam.
            </p>

            <p>
                The argument form can be written as:
            </p>

            <p>
                <me>
                    \begin{array}{r} p \Rightarrow q\\ \neg q\\ \hline \neg p \end{array}
                </me>
            </p>
        </example>

        <p>
            When is an argument form accepted to be correct? In normal usage, we use an argument in order to demonstrate that a certain conclusion follows from known premises.
            Therefore, we shall require that under any assignment of truth values to the statements appearing, if the premises became all true, then the conclusion must also become true.
            Hence, we state the following definition.
        </p>
    </paragraphs>


    <paragraphs>
        <title>Validity of Arguments</title>

        <definition>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    An argument form <m>p_1, p_2, p_3, \ldots, p_n \vdash Q</m> is said to be <em>valid</em> if <m>Q</m> is true whenever all the premises <m>p_1, p_2, p_3, \ldots, p_n</m> are true; otherwise it is <em>invalid</em>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </definition>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Investigate the validity of the following arguments:
                </p>

                <p>
                    <ol marker="a. ">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>p \Rightarrow q, \, \neg q \vdash \neg p</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>p \Rightarrow q, \, \neg q \Rightarrow r \vdash p</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                If it rains, crops will be good.
                                It did not rain.
                                Therefore, crops were not good.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <p>
                    First we construct a truth table for the statements appearing in the argument forms.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                            </p>

                            <tabular top="major" bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>p</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>q</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>\neg p</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>\neg q</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>p \Rightarrow q</m></cell>
                                </row>

                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                </row>

                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                </row>

                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                </row>

                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                </row>
                            </tabular>

                            <p>
                                The premises <m>p \Rightarrow q</m> and <m>\neg q</m> are true simultaneously in row 4 only.
                                Since in this case <m>\neg p</m> is also true, the argument is valid.
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <tabular top="major" bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>p</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>q</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>r</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>\neg q</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>p \Rightarrow q</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>\neg q \Rightarrow r</m></cell>
                                </row>

                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                </row>

                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                </row>

                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                </row>

                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                </row>

                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                </row>

                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                </row>

                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                </row>

                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                </row>
                            </tabular>

                            <p>
                                The <m>1^{\text{st}}</m>, <m>2^{\text{nd}}</m>, <m>5^{\text{th}}</m>, <m>6^{\text{th}}</m> and <m>7^{\text{th}}</m> rows are those in which all the premises take value <m>T</m>.
                                In the <m>5^{\text{th}}</m>, <m>6^{\text{th}}</m> and <m>7^{\text{th}}</m> rows however the conclusion takes value <m>F</m>.
                                Hence, the argument form is invalid.
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Let <m>p</m>: It rains.
                            </p>

                            <p>
                                <m>\qquad q</m>: Crops are good.
                            </p>

                            <p>
                                <m>\qquad \neg p</m>: It did not rain.
                            </p>

                            <p>
                                <m>\qquad \neg q</m>: Crops were not good.
                            </p>

                            <p>
                                The argument form is <m>p \Rightarrow q, -p \vdash -q</m>
                            </p>

                            <p>
                                Now we can use truth table to test validity as follows:
                            </p>

                            <tabular top="major" bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>p</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>q</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>\neg p</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>\neg q</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>p \Rightarrow q</m></cell>
                                </row>

                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                </row>

                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                </row>

                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                </row>

                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>F</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>T</m></cell>
                                </row>
                            </tabular>

                            <p>
                                Examining the table, we can see that the premises <m>p \Rightarrow q</m> and <m>\neg p</m> are true in both rows 3 and 4.
                                However, in row 3, <m>\neg q</m> is false, which means the argument is invalid.
                            </p>

                            <p>
                                The premises <m>p \Longrightarrow q</m> and <m>\neg p</m> are true simultaneously in row 4 only.
                                Since in this case <m>\neg q</m> is also true, the argument is valid.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <remark>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            What is important in validity is the form of the argument rather than the meaning or content of the statements involved.
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The argument form <m>p_{1},\ p_{2},p_{3},\ldots,p_{n}\ â”œ\ \ Q</m> is valid iff the statement
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            <m>(p_{1} \land p_{2} \land p_{3} \land \ldots \land p_{n}\ ) \Longrightarrow Q</m> is a tautology.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </remark>
    </paragraphs>


    <paragraphs>
        <title>Rules of Inference</title>
        
        
        <p>
            Below we list certain valid deductions called rules of inferences.
        </p>

        <p>
            <ol marker="1. " cols="2">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Modus Ponens
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <m>\begin{array}{c} p \\ p \implies q \\ \hline q \end{array}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        Modus Tollens
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <m>\begin{array}{c} p \implies q \\ \neg q \\ \hline \neg p \end{array}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        Principle of Syllogism
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <m>\begin{array}{c} p \Rightarrow q \\ q \Rightarrow r \\ \hline p \Rightarrow r \end{array}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        Principle of Adjunction
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <ol marker="a)">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\begin{array}{c} p \\ q \\ \hline p \land q \end{array}</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>

                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\frac{q}{p \lor q}</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        Principle of Detachment
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <m>\begin{array}{c} p \land q \\ \hline p, q \end{array}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        Modus Tollendo Ponens
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <m>\begin{array}{c} \neg p \\ p \lor q \\ \hline q \end{array}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        Modus Ponendo Tollens
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <m>\begin{array}{c} \neg(p \land q) \\ p \\ \hline \neg q \end{array}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        Constructive Dilemma
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <m>\begin{array}{c} (p \Rightarrow q) \land (r \Rightarrow s) \\ p \lor r \\ \hline q \lor s \end{array}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        Principle of Equivalence
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <m>\begin{array}{c} p \Leftrightarrow q \\ p \\ \hline q \end{array}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        Principle of Conditionalization
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <m>\begin{array}{c} p \\ \hline q \Rightarrow p \end{array}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </paragraphs>


    <paragraphs>
        <title>Formal Proofs of Validity</title>

        <p>
            A formal proof demonstrates the validity of an argument using a sequence of logical steps.
        </p>

        <definition>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A formal proof of a conclusion <m>Q</m> given hypotheses <m>p_{1},\ p_{2},p_{3},\ldots,p_{n}</m> is a sequence of steps, each of which applies some inference rule to hypotheses or previously proven statements (antecedent) to yield a new true statement (the consequent).
                </p>
            </statement>
        </definition>

        <p>
            A formal proof of validity is given by writing on the premises and the statements which follows from them in a single column, and setting off in another column, to the right of each statement, its justification.
            It is convenient to list all the premises first.
        </p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Show that <m>p \Longrightarrow \neg q,q \vdash \neg p</m> is valid.
                </p>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <tabular>
                    <col width="80%"/> <col width="20%" halign="right"/>
                    <row>
                        <cell>1. <m>q</m> is true</cell>
                        <cell>premise</cell>
                    </row>

                    <row>
                        <cell>2. <m>p \Longrightarrow \neg q</m> is true</cell>
                        <cell>premise</cell>
                    </row>

                    <row>
                        <cell>3. <m>q \Longrightarrow \neg p</m> is true</cell>
                        <cell>contrapositive of (2)</cell>
                    </row>

                    <row>
                        <cell>4. <m>\neg p</m> is true</cell>
                        <cell>Modus Ponens using (1) and (3)</cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Show that the hypotheses
                </p>

                <blockquote>
                    <p>
                        It is not sunny this afternoon and it is colder than yesterday.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        If we go swimming, then it is sunny.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        If we do not go swimming, then we will take a canoe trip.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        If we take a canoe trip, then we will be home by sunset.
                    </p>
                </blockquote>

                <p>
                    Lead to the conclusion: 
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>\qquad</m> We will be home by sunset. 
                </p>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <p>
                    Let <m>p</m>: It is sunny this afternoon.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <m>\qquad q</m>: It is colder than yesterday.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <m>\qquad r</m>: We go swimming.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <m>\qquad s</m>: We take a canoe trip.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <m>\qquad t</m>: We will be home by sunset.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Then
                </p>

                <tabular>
                    <col width="80%"/> <col width="20%" halign="right"/>
                    <row>
                        <cell>1. <m>\neg p \land q</m></cell>
                        <cell>hypothesis</cell>
                    </row>

                    <row>
                        <cell>2. <m>\neg p</m></cell>
                        <cell>simplification using (1)</cell>
                    </row>

                    <row>
                        <cell>3. <m>r \implies p</m></cell>
                        <cell>hypothesis</cell>
                    </row>

                    <row>
                        <cell>4. <m>\neg r</m></cell>
                        <cell>Modus Tollens using (2) and (3)</cell>
                    </row>

                    <row>
                        <cell>5. <m>\neg r \implies s</m></cell>
                        <cell>hypothesis</cell>
                    </row>

                    <row>
                        <cell>6. <m>s</m></cell>
                        <cell>Modus Ponens using (4) and (5)</cell>
                    </row>

                    <row>
                        <cell>7. <m>s \implies t</m></cell>
                        <cell>hypothesis</cell>
                    </row>

                    <row>
                        <cell>8. <m>t</m></cell>
                        <cell>Modus Ponens using (6) and (7)</cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </paragraphs>

    <exercises>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Use the truth table method to show that the following argument forms are valid.
            </p>

            <p>
                <ol marker="i">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\neg p \Longrightarrow \neg q,\ q\ \vdash\ p</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>p \Longrightarrow \neg p,\ p,\ r \Longrightarrow q\ \vdash\ \neg r</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>p \Longrightarrow q,\ \neg r \Longrightarrow \neg q\ \vdash \neg r \Longrightarrow \neg p</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\neg r \vee \neg s,\ (\neg s \Longrightarrow p) \Longrightarrow r\ \vdash\ \neg p</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>p \Longrightarrow q,\ \neg p \Longrightarrow r,\ r \Longrightarrow s \vdash\ \neg q \Longrightarrow s</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                For the following arguments given a, b and c below:
            </p>

            <ol marker="i">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Identify the premises.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        Write argument forms.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        Check the validity.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>

            <ol marker="a">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\qquad</m> If he studies medicine, he will get a good job.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <m>\qquad</m> If he gets a good job, he will get a good wage.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <m>\qquad</m> He did not get a good wage.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <m>\qquad</m> Therefore, he did not study medicine.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\qquad</m> If the team is late, then it cannot play the game.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <m>\qquad</m> If the referee is here, then the team can play the game.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <m>\qquad</m> The team is late.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <m>\qquad</m> Therefore, the referee is not here.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\qquad</m> If the professor offers chocolate for an answer, you answer the professor's question.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <m>\qquad</m> The professor offers chocolate for an answer.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <m>\qquad</m> Therefore, you answer the professor's question.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Give formal proof to show that the following argument forms are valid.
            </p>

            <p>
                <ol marker="a. ">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\neg p \Longrightarrow \neg q,\ q\ \vdash\ p</m>.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>p \Longrightarrow \neg q,\ p,\ r \Longrightarrow q\ \vdash\ \neg r</m>.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>p \Longrightarrow q,\ \neg r \Longrightarrow \neg q\ \vdash\ \neg r \Longrightarrow \neg p</m>.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\neg r \land \neg s,\ (\neg s \Longrightarrow p) \Longrightarrow r\ \vdash\ \neg p</m>.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>p \Longrightarrow q,\ \neg p \Longrightarrow r,\ r \Longrightarrow s\ \vdash\ \neg q \Longrightarrow s</m>.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\neg p \vee q,\ r \Longrightarrow p,\ r\ \vdash\ q</m>.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\neg p \land \neg q,\ (q \vee r) \Longrightarrow p\ \vdash\ \neg r</m>.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>p \Longrightarrow (q \vee r),\ \neg r,\ p\ \vdash\ q</m>.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\neg q \Longrightarrow \neg p,\ r \Longrightarrow p,\ \neg q\ \vdash\ r</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>

